  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol, also known as copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O), changes its color from blue to white upon heating due to the loss of water molecules that are chemically bound within its crystal structure.\n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Hydrated Form**: In its natural state, blue vitriol is hydrated, meaning it contains water molecules (H\u2082O) associated with the copper sulfate. The chemical formula of the hydrated form is CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O. The water molecules are held in place by weak bonds within the crystal lattice.\n\n2. **Effect of Heating**: When blue vitriol is heated, the thermal energy causes the water molecules to break free from the crystal structure. This process is called **dehydration**.\n\n3. **Anhydrous Form**: Once the water molecules are removed, the compound becomes anhydrous copper(II) sulfate (CuSO\u2084). The anhydrous form is white in color, unlike the blue hydrated form.\n\n4. **Color Change**: The blue color of the hydrated copper(II) sulfate is due to the presence of water molecules in the crystal structure, which influence the way the compound absorbs and reflects light. When the water is removed, the color changes to white because the anhydrous form has different light absorption properties.\n\n### Reversibility:\nThis process is reversible. If water is added to the anhydrous white copper(II) sulfate, it will rehydrate and return to its original blue color.\n\n### Summary:\nThe color change from blue to white upon heating is due to the loss of water molecules from the crystal structure of copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate, converting it into anhydrous copper(II) sulfate.",
